---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Container from '@mcp-orchestrator/design-system/components/Container.astro';
import Card from '@mcp-orchestrator/design-system/components/Card.astro';
import Stack from '@mcp-orchestrator/design-system/components/Stack.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — asc.engineering"
  description="Background, education, and professional journey of Dr. Andreas Schlapbach."
>
  <section class="py-16">
    <Container maxWidth="4xl" size="sm">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-8 text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        About Me
      </h2>

      <Stack direction="vertical" size="md">
        <Card variant="default" size="md">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
            Background
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            I'm an AI/ML Initiative Lead and Enterprise Architect based in Muri
            bei Bern, Switzerland. With over 25 years of experience building
            large-scale distributed systems, I've worked at the intersection of
            software architecture, distributed computing, machine learning,
            and—most recently—agentic AI systems.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white pt-3">
            Career Path
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            My career has evolved across three distinct chapters:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            <li class="pt-1">
              <strong
                >Enterprise Architecture & AI Systems (2013–Present):</strong
              >
              Led architecture for SBB's omni-channel distribution, next-generation
              web presence (sbb.ch), and—most recently—agentic ecosystems using the
              Model Context Protocol.
            </li>
            <li class="pt-1">
              <strong>Machine Learning & Document Analysis (2004–2011):</strong> Applied
              statistical learning (HMM, GMM, SVM) to handwriting recognition and
              writer identification, contributing to pattern recognition and document
              image analysis.
            </li>
            <li class="pt-1">
              <strong>Software Composition & Reengineering (2001–2003):</strong> Focused
              on formal methods (π-calculus), meta-modeling (MOF/XMI), and component-oriented
              programming at the University of Bern.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white pt-3">
            Current Focus
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            I lead AI/ML initiatives at SBB's Passenger Division, designing
            ecosystems of domain-expert agents coordinated via the Model Context
            Protocol (MCP). My recent work explores formal verification of
            agentic systems, schema-driven interoperability, and scaling
            LLM-powered tools across large organizations.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white pt-3">
            Education
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            <ul
              class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400"
            >
              <li class="pt-1">
                <strong>PhD in Computer Science</strong> — University of Bern, 2008.
                Dissertation: "Writer Identification and Verification."
              </li>
              <li class="pt-1">
                <strong>Diplom (Master's)</strong> — University of Bern, 2002. Thesis:
                "Enabling White-Box Reuse in a Pure Composition Language" (<a
                  class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
                  href="https://scg.unibe.ch/research/piccola"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">JPiccola</a
                >).
              </li>
              <li class="pt-1">
                <strong>Bachelor's</strong> — University of Bern, 2001. Thesis: "Generic
                XMI Support for the MOOSE Reengineering Environment."
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white pt-3">
            Open Source & Community
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            I'm a long-standing contributor to open-source projects, including
            contributions to the KDE HTML rendering engine (khtml) and <a
              class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
              href="https://webkit.org/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">WebKit</a
            >
            CSS parser. I'm also the Technical Lead and Product Owner of the <a
              class="text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 hover:text-accent-600 dark:hover:text-accent-300 transition-colors"
              href="https://osdm.org/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              >Open Sales and Distribution Model (OSDM)</a
            >, an international API standard for rail ticket distribution, now
            adopted by all major European railways and leading global
            distribution systems.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white pt-3">
            Interests
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            Beyond work, I'm fascinated by the intersection of formal methods
            and practical systems, the challenges of scaling machine learning in
            production, and the emerging paradigm of agentic AI. I believe the
            future of enterprise software lies in intelligent, schema-driven
            agent ecosystems that can dynamically compose tools across
            organizational and domain boundaries.
          </p>
        </Card>
      </Stack>
    </Container>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
